There are two main approaches to running a crypto exchange in 2022:
=09You set up a centralized exchange in some country. You form a corporatio=
n, the corporation runs the exchange, it opens accounts and holds crypto fo=
r customers, and you try to be a good corporate citizen. You follow the cou=
ntry=E2=80=99s laws as much as possible, and you lobby to change the ones y=
ou don=E2=80=99t like. Exactly how regulated you are (and how much lobbying=
 clout you have) depends on the country, and this approach encompasses both=
 =E2=80=9Cincorporate in the US and beg the Securities and Exchange Commiss=
ion for permission to do anything at all=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cincorporate =
in a small island nation, buy its political system and do whatever you want=
.=E2=80=9D Both have pluses and minuses: The buy-an-island approach gives y=
ou a lot of flexibility and probably nice weather; the US approach gives yo=
u access to a lot of customers and, arguably, the confidence-boosting value=
 of US regulatory oversight.=09You set up a decentralized exchange with no =
legal entities at all, or at least none that run the exchange. The exchange=
 consists of smart contracts that run permanently on some blockchain; peopl=
e can interact with the exchange in a purely decentralized, permissionless =
way. You might try to avoid personal criminal liability by not coding or ad=
vertising the exchange in a way that is going to get you obviously arrested=
 by US authorities, or alternatively by being anonymous and staying away fr=
om the US. But even if you do get arrested, the exchange is open and decent=
ralized and hard to shut down. It exists not in a corporate entity but in c=
ode on a decentralized censorship-resistant blockchain.

I have   suggested in the past =E2=80=94=C2=A0very much without giving lega=
l advice! =E2=80=94=C2=A0that the second approach, empirically,=C2=A0works:=
=C2=A0US regulators abstractly, and sometimes concretely, do not like the i=
dea that decentralized finance is insulated from regulatory oversight, but =
in practice it seems to be kind of true.
  [7]
=C2=A0The exchanges that are most subject to regulation are the ones that p=
ick up the phone when regulators call. If you don=E2=80=99t have a phone nu=
mber, they can never call you.
Anyway I guess a third approach is: Set up a centralized exchange, form lik=
e 100 corporations in different countries, and=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t tell anyo=
ne which one runs the exchange?=C2=A0That is extremely not legal advice but=
  here=E2=80=99s Reuters on Binance:

Described on its website as an =E2=80=9Cecosystem=E2=80=9D with over 120 mi=
llion users, Binance has set up at least 73 companies across the world, acc=
ording to corporate filings and company organisation charts. [Founder Chang=
peng =E2=80=9CCZ=E2=80=9D] Zhao owns or partly controls at least 59. He dec=
lines to give details of the location or entity behind the main exchange, w=
hich makes money by charging fees on crypto trades. =E2=80=A6
One example of his oversight came in early 2020. A London-based payments pa=
rtner called Checkout.com asked Binance to state on its website that one of=
 Binance=E2=80=99s British units =E2=80=9Cshall be responsible for transact=
ions=E2=80=9D conducted using traditional money. A Checkout.com spokesperso=
n said the request was =E2=80=9Ccompletely standard across the payments and=
 commerce worlds.=E2=80=9D
A Binance employee raised a warning about the requested statement in a mess=
age exchange that included Zhao and other executives. The employee cautione=
d that the statement would leave a =E2=80=9Cpaper trail=E2=80=9D linking th=
e British unit to the main exchange, which Binance has shielded from global=
 regulators by not providing details of its location.

You know US regulators won=E2=80=99t like this, but you can distract them b=
y giving them a US entity to chew on:

Harry Zhou ran a U.S. crypto trading firm that Binance had invested in. He =
sent a proposal to a Binance executives=E2=80=99 message group to address =
=E2=80=9CBinance-specific risks in the US.=E2=80=9D Zhou suggested what he =
described as a =E2=80=9CTai-Chi entity,=E2=80=9D a reference to a martial a=
rt with defensive virtues.=C2=A0...
Binance would restrict U.S. customers=E2=80=99 access to the main platform,=
 the presentation said. But Binance would enable =E2=80=9Cstrategic=E2=80=
=9D use of virtual private networks, which obscure the location of internet=
